?? Basic Linux Commands
?? File & Directory Management
ls        # List files and directories
pwd       # Show current directory
cd        # Change directory
mkdir     # Create a new directory
rmdir     # Remove empty directory
rm        # Remove files or directories
cp        # Copy files/directories
mv        # Move or rename files
?? File Viewing & Editing
cat       # Display file content
less      # View file page by page
nano      # Simple text editor
vim       # Advanced text editor
?? Searching & Filtering
find      # Search for files
grep      # Search text inside files
?? System Information
uname -a  # System information
top       # Monitor system processes
df -h     # Disk usage
free -h   # Memory usage
?? Package Management (Ubuntu/Debian)
sudo apt update      # Update package list
sudo apt upgrade     # Upgrade packages
sudo apt install     # Install a package
sudo apt remove      # Remove a package
?? Permissions & Ownership
chmod     # Change file permissions
chown     # Change file ownership
?? Networking
ping      # Check connectivity
ifconfig  # Network configuration (older)
ip addr   # Show IP address
?? Pro Tips
Use man <command> to read the manual (e.g., man ls)
Use history to view previously used commands
Tab completion helps you auto-complete commands and file names
?? Conclusion

Linux is a powerful and flexible operating system that gives users full control over their environment. Mastering basic commands is the first step toward becoming efficient in Linux.

